  "prompt": "What is a \"point\" in loan-sharking slang?",
  "response": "In the context of loan-sharking or illegal lending, a \"point\" typically refers to a percentage of the loan amount that is charged as interest or fee. Specifically:\n\n- **One point** usually equals **1%** of the loan amount.  \n- For example, if someone borrows $1,000 and the lender charges **3 points**, the borrower would owe an additional $30 (3% of $1,000) as interest or a fee.\n\nThis term is often used to describe the high-interest rates or fees associated with illegal lending practices, which can quickly escalate the amount owed by the borrower. Loan sharks may use this system to exploit borrowers, particularly those who have limited access to traditional financial services.",
